---
import Layout from "@/components/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="Methodology">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="section-label"><span>How GitBench Works</span></div>

    <div
      class="space-y-6 text-sm text-[var(--color-text-mid)] leading-relaxed max-w-3xl"
    >
      <section>
        <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-[var(--color-text)] mb-2">
          Benchmark Design
        </h3>
        <p>
          A benchmark <em>fixture</em> is a single test case: a prompt describing
          a Git task (e.g., "show the last 3 commits as one-liners"), an expected
          output (the correct command or output), and a scoring configuration. Fixtures
          are defined in YAML files under the <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >fixtures/</code
          > directory and grouped into benchmarks by Git task domain.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          The current benchmark suite covers ~17 domains, including
          <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >log</code
          >,
          <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >branch</code
          >,
          <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >commit</code
          >,
          <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >rebase</code
          >,
          <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >merge</code
          >,
          <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >bisect</code
          >,
          <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >cherry-pick</code
          >, and more. Each fixture runs in an isolated Git repository set up
          specifically for that test, ensuring deterministic execution.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-[var(--color-text)] mb-2">
          Similarity Scoring
        </h3>
        <p>
          Each model output is compared to the expected answer using a fuzzy
          similarity algorithm (Python's <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            title="difflib.SequenceMatcher — Python's fuzzy string comparison algorithm."
            >SequenceMatcher</code
          > from the standard library). The similarity score ranges from 0% (completely
          different) to 100% (exact match). A fixture is marked as <strong
            >passed</strong
          > when the similarity exceeds the fixture's configured threshold (typically
          80–90%, depending on the prompt).
        </p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          Similarity scoring is an approximation of correctness — a high score
          means the output is textually close to the expected answer, which
          nearly always correlates with a correct Git command. However,
          semantically equivalent but differently-phrased answers may score
          lower than expected, and near-matches may occasionally be false
          positives.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-[var(--color-text)] mb-2">
          Pass@k Metric
        </h3>
        <p>
          The <strong>pass@k</strong> metric is the proportion of fixtures a model
          passed:
        </p>
        <div
          class="bg-[var(--color-surface)] border border-[var(--color-border)] rounded-lg p-4 my-3 font-mono text-xs"
        >
          pass@k = passed_fixtures / total_fixtures
        </div>
        <p>
          For single-run evaluations (the default), <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >k = 1</code
          >. When a model is run multiple times, <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >k</code
          > represents the number of runs, and pass@k is computed per benchmark or
          across all benchmarks. Pass rates are shown as percentages on the Overview
          and model detail pages.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-[var(--color-text)] mb-2">
          Model Selection &amp; Run Metadata
        </h3>
        <p>
          Models are called through <strong
            ><span title="OpenRouter — unified API gateway for AI model access."
              >OpenRouter</span
            ></strong
          > (for cloud-hosted models) or a local <strong
            ><span title="Ollama — runs AI models locally on your hardware."
              >Ollama</span
            ></strong
          > server. Each run records:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside mt-2 space-y-1 font-mono text-xs">
          <li>
            <code>profile</code> — the runner profile used (e.g., "openrouter")
          </li>
          <li>
            <code>git_sha</code> — the GitBench commit hash at the time of the run
          </li>
          <li>
            <code>benchmark_suite_version</code> — version of the benchmark suite
          </li>
          <li><code>timestamp</code> — UTC timestamp of the run</li>
          <li>
            <code>reasoning_level</code> — optional reasoning effort level (e.g.,
            "low", "high") for models that support it
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-2">
          Model names may include a <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >#level</code
          > suffix to specify a reasoning effort level. For example, <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >o3-mini#high</code
          >
          runs the o3-mini model with high reasoning effort. The base model name is
          used for grouping.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-[var(--color-text)] mb-2">
          Cost Data
        </h3>
        <p>
          When models are called through OpenRouter, the API response includes a
          <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >cost</code
          > field (in USD). GitBench extracts this cost and surfaces it on the Models
          overview page (per-model total and average cost) and on the Cost vs Quality
          quadrant chart. Models run through Ollama do not produce cost data and will
          show "—" for cost fields.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          Raw run files in <code
            class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded"
            >gitbench-results/</code
          >
          remain untouched and contain the full run data, including any models filtered
          from the UI output.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-[var(--color-text)] mb-2">
          Limitations
        </h3>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1">
          <li>
            Only measures <strong>output correctness</strong> — does not evaluate
            speed, UX, multi-turn reasoning, or tool use.
          </li>
          <li>
            Results <strong>vary by run</strong> — LLM outputs are non-deterministic.
            Pass rates should be treated as estimates, not absolute scores.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Similarity scoring is approximate</strong> — a correct answer
            with different phrasing may score lower; an incorrect but similar-looking
            answer may pass.
          </li>
          <li>
            Only <strong>open-weight models available through OpenRouter</strong
            > (or local Ollama models) are tested. Proprietary model evaluation depends
            on API access.
          </li>
          <li>
            The benchmark suite is <strong>under active development</strong>.
            New fixtures and benchmarks are added regularly, and scoring
            thresholds may be tuned over time.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
